article.headline: Minnesota wins conference opener
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Coach Pam Borton was pleased with No. 12
Minnesota's defensive effort in a 62-44 win over Northwestern to
open Big Ten play.

The Gophers forced 14 turnovers, had 10 steals and limited the
overmatched Wildcats to 16-of-33 shooting.

"On the offensive end, it's a work in progress," Borton said.

Only Janel McCarville reached double figures with 13 points,
adding 14 rebounds for her 38th career double-double.

"Our defense is probably better right now than it's been all
year," said Borton. "That's where we get our identity, that's
where we get our energy so we can play an up-tempo game. We've got
to execute our half-court sets a little better."

McCarville was just 5-of-13 from the field for Minnesota (11-2).

"It's always good to start out the Big Ten season with a win,
no matter who you're playing," McCarville said.

Ifeoma Okonkwo scored 18 and Samantha McComb had 10 for
injury-depleted Northwestern, which dressed just eight players.

Trailing throughout the game, the Wildcats cut Minnesota's lead
to 48-36 on a 3-pointer by Melissa Culver.

"I thought we could maybe make a run and cut it to single
digits," said Northwestern coach Beth Combs. "Great teams make
great plays when they need them, and that's what Minnesota did."

McCarville got the Gophers back on track by taking a pass from
Shannon Schonrock for an easy basket, then finished off a couple of
defensive stops with a steal and a pair of rebounds. Natasha
Williams' jump hook with 3:31 remaining pushed Minnesota's lead to
57-47.

Minnesota has started the Big Ten season with a win all three
seasons under Borton.

The Gophers took control by holding the Wildcats (3-11) to one
field goal over a 13:02 span.

McCarville keyed the 24-4 spurt with a basket off a nifty inside
move, a jumper from the lane, a pair of free throws, and a backdoor
bounce pass leading to a layup by April Calhoun. A 3-pointer and
two free throws by Shannon Bolden pushed Minnesota's lead to 36-15.

"I'm definitely starting to feel more comfortable, knowing what
my role is and what shots are mine to take," said Calhoun, in her
first year with the Gophers after transferring from Iowa, where she
played two seasons.
